abstract: David Oscar helped start an L.G.B.T. & Allies meeting at a group home in the Bronx because “I felt that the world in general was against who I was.”
snippet: David Oscar helped start an L.G.B.T. & Allies meeting at a group home in the Bronx because “I felt that the world in general was against who I was.”
lead_paragraph: RIVERDALE, N.Y. — At the start of a recent meeting of the L.G.B.T. & Allies group at the Hebrew Home here, the group leaders Olivia Cohen and Liisa Murray reminded attendees of the ground rules, which they had written on a poster board.

headline_main: Border Children, North Korea, Global Trade: Your Thursday Briefing

abstract: New York City filed two lawsuits on Wednesday accusing a broker and landlords of not renting apartments to people who receive rental assistance.
snippet: New York City filed two lawsuits on Wednesday accusing a broker and landlords of not renting apartments to people who receive rental assistance.
lead_paragraph: For the past four years, New York City has tried to persuade landlords and real estate brokers to rent apartments to low-income people and homeless people with bonuses and pledges that rent would be guaranteed with government vouchers.

headline_main: New York City Sues Landlords Who Refuse Government Vouchers
headline_print_headline: In Suit, City Accuses Landlords of Refusing to Accept Housing Vouchers

abstract: Mr. Bloomberg plans to pour money into advertising on television, online and in the mail, with most of it going to support Democratic congressional candidates.
snippet: Mr. Bloomberg plans to pour money into advertising on television, online and in the mail, with most of it going to support Democratic congressional candidates.
lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg, the billionaire former mayor of New York City, has decided to throw his political clout and personal fortune behind the Democratic campaign to take control of the House of Representatives this year, directing aides to spend tens of millions of dollars in an effort to expel Republicans from power.

headline_main: DealBook Briefing: The C.E.O.s Taking on Trump Over Immigration

abstract: Increasing the size of congressional districts and number of members elected make the electoral institution less effective.
snippet: Increasing the size of congressional districts and number of members elected make the electoral institution less effective.
lead_paragraph: In the months leading up to Monday’s Supreme Court punt on the gerrymandering cases out of Wisconsin and Maryland, those hoping the court would rein in partisan gerrymanders had been cautiously optimistic. Justice Anthony Kennedy made it known that if a “workable standard” could be found to distinguish legitimate districting from partisan gerrymandering, he might sign onto it. Reformers thought they had found that standard in something called the “efficiency gap.”

headline_main: The Best Way to Fix Gerrymandering Is to Make It Useless

abstract: A selection of recent audiobooks; plus, a peek at what our colleagues around the newsroom are reading.
snippet: A selection of recent audiobooks; plus, a peek at what our colleagues around the newsroom are reading.
lead_paragraph: GOOD NIGHT STORIES FOR REBEL GIRLS By Francesca Cavallo and Elena Favilli. Read by a cast that includes Alicia Keys, Ashley Judd and Esperanza Spalding. (Listening Library.) The 100 stories told here about women scientists, chefs, jazz singers and boxers (among many others) are meant to inspire young girls. THE PATH TO PRIDE By Lance Bass and Nikki Levy. (Audible.) Recorded live and in honor of Pride Month, Bass and others recount their stories about coming out. HOW NOT TO GET SHOT By D. L. Hughley and Doug Moe. Read by Hughley. (HarperAudio.) One of the original “Kings of Comedy,” Hughley interprets the advice he says black people have been receiving from white people for the last four centuries (ever since “I suggest you pick the cotton if you don’t like getting whipped”). A satirical but apt addition to the culture’s fraught conversation about race. THE HIGH SEASON By Judy Blundell. Read by Julia Whelan. (Random House Audio.) Blundell tells the story of a summer in the Hamptons, with the rich and beautiful seen through the eyes of a local. HAS ANYONE SEEN THE PRESIDENT? By Michael Lewis. Read by the author. (S&S Audio.) In this audiobook original (which first appeared as an article in Bloomberg Businessweek) Lewis reports on how the nation’s capital has changed in the age of Trump.
